segments.text: research chemist and head of the Texas Engineering Experiment Station Food Protein Division.
Today's date is August 4th, 1981.
Let's begin, Dr. Lucis, by your telling us something about your early years, please.
Well, I grew up on a farm in Woodbury, Connecticut, and it was a general purpose and dairy farm.
And I first went to college to become a butter dairy farmer.
And this was at the University of Connecticut in Storrs, Connecticut.
Where?
Storrs.
Spell that.
S-T-O-R-R-S. And while there, my interests turned to food processing.
And my first degree, BS, was in dairy production as well as dairy manufacturing.
When did you get this degree?
This was in 1954.
When did you finish house food?
I spent a year in between dairy farming.
I then went on to Iowa State College at the time.
Before you go on, how far was this part of Connecticut from New York City?
This was about 100 miles, and that was a long way.
100 miles east?
Yeah, northeast.
This was in the southern part of Litchfield County at the Berkshire foothills.
So there are still agricultural and dairy interests in this part of Connecticut?
Very little now.
There probably aren't more than 100 or 150 farms left.
And those are dairy farms.
And there is a lot of truck gardening and also tobacco gardening.
Shade-grown tobacco for cigar wrappings and binders is a very major industry.
The profitability is such that they've been able to continue to use land for that.
OK, you finished that degree in 1954, and then you went to Iowa State.
Iowa State.
At Ames.
At Ames.
Tell me about that.
Well, the way I got there was that in my senior year at Connecticut, I was on a dairy products judging team.
And we were pretty good.
We took first place in the eastern states dairy products judging meet in Springfield, Massachusetts, and then went on to the national meeting, which was held at Boston that year.
And there was a fellowship given to members of each of the top three teams.
And that was my ticket to Iowa State.
I studied in the dairy manufacturing building, as they call it there.
Actually, my degree was in food technology.
At that time, no one quite knew what a food technologist was.
But they were starting to identify that as a separate discipline.
I was there for just about a year.
finished my masters and then went to the University of Wisconsin at Madison.
There I did my PhD in food technology, working primarily on canned vegetable and canned fruit problems.
I finished that degree in 1958.
It also was in food technology.
After that, I went to
Work for the Quaker Oats Company at the John Stewart Research Laboratories in Barrington, Illinois.
Spell that.
Barrington, B-A-R-R-I-N-G-T-O-N. And Quaker, of course, everybody recognizes the little Quaker man in the oatmeal box.
But it was a diversified company.
It had many, many product lines.
It was the largest miller of not only oats, but also of barley and dry corn products, such as white corn grits, yellow corn meal.
They developed a process for making masa harina, M-A-S-A, harina, H-A-R-I-N-A, which is the lime
treated corn that tortillas are made from.
This was really the first convenience type of Mexican food that had been developed, and so the company had many interests.
I was in the food, in the bakery mixes group for the first three years, and because I had had considerable experience
and exposure to canning.
When I worked on canned fruits and vegetables in my PhD, I then transferred over to work on pet foods.
At that time, the U.S. pet foods industry was probably about $800 million a year volume, and Quaker had...
about $60 million of the sales.
It was the largest seller of pet foods.
There were very, very many small companies in the area.
Those were very exciting years because it was a chance to pull many things together.
One of the things that I did was organize the research program at Quaker Oats
I started with a staff of two, and 12 years later had a staff of 32 people.
We developed numerous products, expanded the U.S. product line from five products to about 30 in that period, developed processes that allowed the company to enter other markets
put up plants in Holland, England, Australia, and also expand the line, the cattle ration and Puss in Boots lines in Canada.
During that 12-year period, the sales of pet foods rose from about $60 million to close to $280 million.
Uh, so it was very exciting period.
Uh, this was still at Barrington, Illinois, still at Barrington, Illinois.
Um, the pet foods industry was growing about twice as fast or nearly three times as fast as, uh, as grocery products industry.
And there was the, uh, uh,

leader in development of new types of, and application of new types of technologies such as continuous retorts, development of semi-moist pet foods which are preserved by controlling the water activity.
In other words, by use of high osmotic pressure, this means sugar, salt, and
as well as pH control.
Since then, quite a few products have been developed and marketed, but we were pioneers at the time.
What was the reason for this boom in pet food during this period?
Well, there were several reasons.
The world was going through a rather affluent stage.
Much of Europe had been rebuilt.
After the war, business conditions were pretty good, and there were something like about 25 million dogs at the time in the U.S., and about the same number of cats, probably about 22 million cats.
And people were becoming conscious about their pets, and they were starting to treat them as...
well, as surrogate children.
In some cases, even taking better care of them than with their own kids.
Of course, when you are working with pet food, you are in an area of food technology, which is a cross between, say, human food science and animal feeding science.
You're
products are sold in grocery stores.
And therefore, they have to be attractive and pleasant in appearance and in odor when they're brought into the household.
On the other hand, in the 50 states, the regulations and requirements are set by the respective state feed control officials.
So when you are working on pet foods,
You have to abide by these various state laws as well as also take full responsibility for the nutrition of the animal.
This is one thing that we aren't yet doing in food.
We give people free choice, but when you have a pet and it relies entirely on you for its sustenance, someone has to worry about its nutrition.
Pets do go through a life cycle, and there are different nutrition needs from, say, puppyhood through growth, reproduction, and then on into the older ages.
You do get a very good overview of nutrition in application when you work in the pet food area.
You worked in that from 58 to 70?
From 58 to about 1971.
At that time, I had been, no, let's see, I worked in pet foods from 61 to about 71.
At that time, I, let me shut that off.
Well, I don't want to answer that.
You can just wait.
You said you worked in the Pet Food Division from 61 to 71.
Right.
At that time, I became interested in other areas.
And I found that the world really wasn't giving
or recognizing the pet food technologists as being part of the food science area.
And by this time, I had amassed quite a large staff and realized that after this, most of my future would be in management and administration.
So I took a two-year course in the Graduate School of Business at the University of Chicago.
in their executive program.
This was a fixed curriculum program, which led to an MBA in two years.
And it was a type of course where you still continued your job full time.
One week went to two classes, all day classes on Friday on the company's time and next week went all day Saturday on your own time.
There were two sessions or two groups that went simultaneously through the program and they would alternate Fridays and Saturdays.
It took about 30 hours a week.
to take the course on top of your regular program.
So it was just like signing up for law school, things like that.
This is 1970.
I completed the Master's of Business Administration in 1972.
In 1971, the company divisionalized.
The sales of the company had grown from something like about $90 million a year to well over a billion and a half.
in the previous 15 years, and there were many new groups organized, and I took on the position of Manager of Scientific Services.
This was running the
services in common for the various research programs at the Barrington Laboratories.
I had 65 people at the time, and we ran the analytical laboratory, microbiology, biochemistry research, statistics, operations research, and data processing.
These were
programs that served not only the people in the research laboratories, but also at the various plants as the need arose.
I held that position until 1977, at which time I came to Texas A&M University.
What was the circumstances of your coming here?
The Food Protein Research and Development Center had lost its associate director, Dr. Carl Kater, C-A-T-E-R, the previous October.
It's Carl with a C or a K. C-A-R-L.
I believe it was in October.
I'm sorry, it was the previous November.
in an airplane accident.
He was flying his private plane to a meeting in Peoria, Illinois, and had an accident.
The position was open, and so I came on board as an associate director of research, realizing at the time that this was a training position for
becoming director since the then director, Dr. Carl Mattil, that's K-A-R-L, Mattil, M-A-T-T-I-L, had had a heart attack several years earlier and was working part time.
He didn't look very good at the time of the interview.
Um, and, uh, but I still thought he probably would, um, uh, would be active for another year or two.

Uh, however, when I got here, um, he had, had become quite disabled and, uh, uh, went in the hospital shortly thereafter and died, uh, not from a heart attack, but from, um, pancreatic cancer, which is a very painful way to go.
I really spent very little time with Dr. Mattil because of the circumstances.
And so essentially, here I was having two positions to fill.
And I had just arrived from industry.
Carl Mattil died in October of 1977.
There were plans at the time on the drawing board for developing or building a new building.
Actually, it was a program to move the Food Protein Research and Development Center out of Central Campus.
The original building had been donated to the university by the
Texas Cotton Seed Processors Committee back in the mid-1940s.
And it had a solvent extraction plant along with it, and this was right next to the boiler house or the boiler plant in Central Campus.
Of course, as the university had grown, it had had to expand its
utilities, including the steam generation and water chilling facilities, and it badly needed that space to expand the central power plant.
Our building was fairly old and inadequate at the time, and so an exchange was made.
They built new buildings for us, the research oil mill out at the
Texas A&M Research Annex at West Highway 21 in Bryan.
That's the site of the former Bryan Air Force Base.
And the new Food Protein Research and Development main building was built in West Campus, just west of the railroad tracks, beyond Wellborn Road and the south of
University Avenue, just south of the agricultural engineering shops.
Um, as I was mentioning earlier, the plans were there, but, uh, but they weren't finalized.
And so one of my first duties was to, uh, finalize the, uh, list of requirements.
And, um,
and then work with the architect in designing the building.
Of course, making various compromises since everyone's operating under a budget.
We moved first into the research oil mill in the summer of 1979.
We had shut down some of the
research program, particularly the salmon extraction plant.

I moved that in the summer of 1979, and then moved the rest of the equipment out in the summer of 1980, as well as moving some equipment to the new Food Protein Research and Development Center building.
and the laboratories.
At that time, the center operated in four locations.
I had moved the main office to the Oilseed Products Building, which was at the corner of Ireland and Ross.
Ireland and Ross Streets.
The main, let's see, the newer laboratories were in the O&ET building.
Dr. K.C.
Rhee, that's K-H-E-E, Choon, C-H-O-O-N, Rhee, capital R-H-E-E, had laboratories in the agronomy field laboratory.
near the veterinary school.
And we also had a fish protein concentrate plant at the Texas A&M Research Annex.
Through our moving, we consolidated the facilities into two locations, the research oil mill at the Texas A&M Research Extension Center and the main building on campus.
What was the cost of this building?
The total building program was about $3.2 million.
This was more than we had anticipated.
Approximately $400,000 was spent on the two Butler-type buildings at the
a research oil mill.
There's about 12,000 square feet there, about 1,500 in the solvent extraction plant, and 10,500 in the seed cleaning and processing building.
The main building on campus
has 28,000 square feet, and it costs about $2.6 million.
Funds for these facilities came from the university permanent fund, and another
$200,000 approximately was contributed by the Texas Engineering Experiment Station from their operating budget.
This was for moving costs, certain components which we needed because we now had split our power plant in two locations.
We did most of the finishing of the research formula ourselves.
This included painting, putting in benches, actually refinishing benches, putting in tile floors, of course, dismantling the old equipment, moving it.
building steel platforms.
In many cases, we had to remodel the equipment as we reinstall it.
Industry was quite helpful.
To this point, we've received about $650,000 worth of equipment and services as either straight donations or long term loans of equipment.
which is the same as the donations as we see it.
In total, I would say we currently have a replacement value of about $6.5 million for our facilities.
We held a industry open house and
dedication program on the 14th and 15th of April, 1981, to commemorate the establishment of these new facilities.
And at that time, through the action of the Board of Regents, the main building was named Cater Matil Hall in honor of Dr. Carl
Mattel and Carl Cater, who were the founders of the Food Protein Research and Development Center.
How many researchers do you have working here?
We have 10 principal investigators.
These are people who lead programs.
In most cases, they are PhDs.
I'd say only two of them are not.
And then they have other advanced degree people working for them.
So we have a total of about 15 advanced degree people in the program.
These researchers, some of these also teach?
Or these are strictly research people?
They teach, but the center is a full-time research program.
We're not an academic group in that we give courses as such or can give degrees.
Our people have cross-appointments in other departments.
Well, soil and crop sciences is probably the major one.
Dr. Ki-Chun Ri, who is now my associate director of research,
has several appointments.
He has an appointment to the graduate school through them and can lead graduate students.
He also is a lecturer, presents two courses under Sonic Crop Sciences.
Dr. Larry Johnson presents a course a year
and is also appointed through the graduate school.
I'm also a professor in soil and crop sciences and have an appointment in the graduate school.
Then we have two people who have cross-appointments in agricultural engineering, Dr. Jose Aguilera.
who teaches a course in food packaging.
Did you spell that last?
Aguilera, A-G-U-I-L-E-R-A.
And he leads graduate students.
And the other person is Dr. Katie Engler.
That's C-A-D-Y Engler, E-N-G-L-E-R. Katie is half-time graduate.
on our program as a half-time teaching appointment in agricultural engineering.
I believe he teaches through a year, probably three different courses, and also leads several graduate students.
Currently, we have about 42 people, nine of whom are associated with the program here.
Nine of them are graduate students.
In many cases, they are
They are here on their own money rather than on half-time assistantships.
We have three visiting scientists, one from Argentina, two from Korea.
And then, of course, we have our secretarial and hourly people that make up the difference
So that 40, what was that?
It's about 42 staff members plus the three visiting scientists.
So 45 would be a better number.
All right.
What are some of the research projects that have recently been completed in food protein?
The one that probably brought the most attention
The most international attention to the center was the development of a process for extracting protein from coconuts and making protein liquid and dry milk products for the Philippine government.
This was a project that was initiated after Dr. Matil toured the world for the AID program.
in the agency for international development.
The project was started in the early 70s.
It took about three or four years to complete.
And we then sent one of our staff members to the Philippines for a two-year period to teach the local people, well, to oversee construction of a pilot plant and to train local staff.
The question is, how do you work with coconuts at college station?
It was simple.
They just would fly them in by plane from the Caribbean several times a month.
Coconuts are fairly stable, and you can keep them refrigerated.
Dr. Hagenmeyer, Hagen, H-A-G-E-N-M-E-I-R, then stayed on with the Philippine Coconut Authority.
has since become a permanent member of their staff.
The Philippine government has decided to build a production plant that faces his early and later process development work.
Here at the center, we're working on a number of interesting projects.
We have taken the lead in the development
processes and food uses for clam is cottonseed.
Normally cottonseed has or contains Gossypol pigment.
Gossypol, G-O-S-S-Y-P-O-L. Pigment which is laid down in small structures called glands.
This is throughout the plant and also in the seed.
And
The gossip ball is toxic to all monogastric animals.
Cattle can handle it well, but chickens, swine, horses, and humans, of course, cannot.
It is possible to detoxify the gossip ball by high temperature heating, but this binds it to the lysine and really diminishes
the food value of the seed.
A new variety of cotton seed was discovered twenty years ago, and its development has continued.
Basically, it's a genetically glandless variety.
The seed just doesn't have the gland
either the glands or the pigments.
And as such, you now have a source of food protein, which is light-colored, very bland, much bland than soybeans, and can be used as a food source.
This should be of particular interest in the world's developing countries because for the most part,
The cultivation of soybeans is limited in the equatorial countries, which tend to be your famine-built countries.
However, cotton is grown in these locations, and it could be a, well, the use of the seed as food would present a,
another crop or return for the same agricultural effort for the same tillage and the same costs of production.
The protein quality of glandless cottonseed is very good.
It's as good or better than soybeans, which would make it probably the world's second best food protein source after rapeseed.
However, rapeseed is a northern-grown crop.
and there still are problems on detoxifying for food use.
So I would say Glynis cottonseed, practically speaking, is a very excellent resource for developing countries.
We have developed techniques for complete de-hulling and separating of Glynis cottonseed.
uh, for roasting the seed, uh, to be used as nut replacements, uh, for making, uh, uh, defatted flowers, protein concentrates, and isolates, and isolates, I-S-O-L-A-T-E-S.
Uh, these are, uh, different degrees of purity of protein.
Normally with most cotton seeds, if you, well, with most seeds, once you get the hull off and the oil out,
Uh, the residue will analyze about 50% protein.
You would take about 5%.
Um, if you then, this would be a flower.
Uh, if you then were to wash the sugars, uh, out of the seed or out of say ground seed, uh, you would raise the protein count to about 70% and this would be the concentrate.
If you then were to further purify the protein, such as by solubilizing in alkali and then re-precipitating with acid, you would have a isolate, which would be about 90% protein.
These are the traditional ways of making various types of food proteins.
We have gone beyond this.
by fractionating the isolates into three fractions.
The whey proteins, the storage and non-storage proteins, and each fraction has a different characteristic, in some cases a somewhat different nutritional value.
The whey proteins are
are very high quality nutrition-wise and are very similar to the whey proteins of milk, for example, or say the whey that results from making cheese.
They would be nutritionally probably the equivalent of egg protein, which is considered to be the highest quality protein readily available for people.
Cotton seed has, in the storage protein, has a fraction that is acid soluble.
In other words, you could make fortified orange juices, soda pop type products, things of this nature.
So there's a lot of versatility.
But what we have done with cotton seed, we have done
with most of the other oilseeds.
This includes soybeans, peanuts, sunflower.
In fact, in sunflower we have learned how to keep the chlorogenic acid, which is one of the compounds or components from turning green during the preparation of isolates.
As a result, you have a white isolate that can be used in many food products.
Dr. Aguilera has worked on processing and utilization of lupin.
This is because of his earlier interest.
He's a native Chilean who has received his last two degrees at US universities.
And lupin is used as a food product in the L-U-P-I-N-A.
It is used as a food source in Chile, and its interest is increasing in other countries.
What is the state that it comes in?
Well, it's a seed.
It's something like a flat pea, and there are various types.
The traditional types do have, well, they have better components, thioglycosinolates, which are,
which are toxic and normally have to be soaked or leached out before processing.
However, there are newer varieties, which are called the sweet-type lupins, where these components have been bred out of the plant.
This results in a really useful food ingredient.
We're pioneering other areas at the center.
One of the processes has been this extraction process originally developed for the production of food protein from coconuts.
In the wet coconut meat, protein is present only at about the 4% level, and there is a lot of fiber.
that occurs with the protein.
The problem there is how to extract this dilute amount of protein and concentrate it.
A wet or aqueous extraction process was developed.
This process primarily uses dairy type centrifuges for separating the oil from the protein, as well as various sieves and
and decanters in the watering devices.
Finally, you end up with a concentrated protein solution, which is dried on a spray dryer.
This process has since been adapted to other oil seeds, such as soybeans, peanuts, sesame, and other products.
And it shows considerable promise for the future because it is a way of extracting oil without using solvents.
Most of the, well, I'd say all of the U.S. soy beans that are processed are extracted with hexane.
And much of the other oil seeds are also similarly processed.
Well, hexane is made from,
Petroleum hexane, H-E-X-A-N-E.
It's derived from the cracking of petroleum.
It's become expensive.
It costs probably about $1.60 to $2 a gallon, depending upon the volume that you buy it in.
It's scarce, and it's more flammable or more combustible than gasoline.
So one has to be very careful when you're going to sell an extraction plant.
There also has been concerns about the residual petroleum, about petroleum residues in food products such as hexane extracted food flowers.
All these problems are solved when you use aqueous extraction processing.
The center also has pioneered in the
application of industrial membranes.
This is reverse osmosis and ultrafiltration to processing of proteins and other agricultural extractives.
The ultrafiltration membranes are used to separate or sieve out, if you want to say
proteins from the other soluble and the reverse osmosis is used to remove the water from the sugars and soluble salts and things of that nature.
Through this technique, you not only recover, through a combination of these techniques, you not only recover more soluble protein, but you also
can get 75% of your water back for recycling.
In other words, for reuse in the next batch process.
Originally, the center got into the program to apply industrial membranes as pollution control devices, but later found that these techniques were useful.

uh processing technologies and from there we from there on we went on to develop processes specifically using membranes we currently are working on processes using stage membranes in other words these membranes being for practical purposes sieves can be staged in series or you know call them stacked so that you do so you can't take
separate proteins into fractions.

Most oilseeds have four or more fractions of proteins, and we feel that we can separate these fractions commercially and at low cost, and therefore would have new type of food ingredients available to us.
In the processing of agricultural crops, there really are two industries.
The first is the industry that breaks the crops or extracts it, mills it into the ingredient, and then the grocery products industry, or say the institutional products industry, which then
compounds these into products that appear on the grocery shelf or are shipped to McDonald's as ready mixes or to bakeries.
We have taken the position that we'll work on the earlier phases that of developing new ingredients from agricultural crops rather than compete with the food.
